layout: base.njk
title: "What is GaaS? The Complete Guide to Agentic as a Service (2026)"
description: "Learn what Agentic as a Service (GaaS) means, how it differs from SaaS, real-world use cases, and why businesses are adopting autonomous AI agents. Complete beginner's guide."
permalink: /resources/what-is-gaas/
faqs:
  - question: "What does GaaS stand for?"
    answer: "GaaS stands for 'Agentic as a Service.' It's a cloud delivery model where autonomous AI agents are deployed as managed services to execute business tasks independently, without requiring human operation for each action."
  - question: "Is GaaS the same as AI automation?"
    answer: "No. Traditional AI automation follows predefined rules and workflows. GaaS agents are autonomous—they can plan, decide, and adapt to new situations. Automation does what you program. GaaS agents figure out what to do based on goals you provide."
  - question: "Do I need technical skills to use GaaS?"
    answer: "No. GaaS is designed for delegation, not programming. You describe what you want accomplished in plain language, and the agent handles the technical execution. It's like hiring a capable assistant rather than writing software."
  - question: "How is GaaS priced?"
    answer: "GaaS uses Cost-per-Outcome (CPO) pricing. Instead of paying monthly fees per user seat, you pay for completed tasks—documents processed, leads generated, code deployed, etc. You only pay when the agent delivers results."
  - question: "Is GaaS secure for sensitive business data?"
    answer: "Yes, when implemented properly. Enterprise GaaS platforms like Zunkiree Labs use ephemeral sandboxed environments, Human-in-the-Loop approval gates for high-risk actions, end-to-end encryption, and comprehensive audit logging."
  - question: "What's the difference between GaaS and hiring contractors?"
    answer: "GaaS agents work 24/7 without breaks, can be scaled instantly (deploy 1,000 agents in minutes vs. months of hiring), cost a fraction of human labor for routine tasks, and maintain perfect consistency. However, they complement rather than replace humans for judgment-heavy work."
